In [[Scots law]], an interdict is a court order to stop someone from breaching someone else's rights.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dwf.law/news-events/legal-updates/2015/06/interdicts-and-exposure/ |title=Interdicts and Exposure |last=Campbell |first=Kenneth |date=29 July 2015 |access-date=17 May 2016 |website=DWF}}</ref> They can be issued by the [[Court of Session]] or a [[Sheriff court|Sheriff Court]]. The equivalent term in England is an [[Injunctions in English law|injunction]]. A temporary interdict is called an interim interdict.<ref>{{cite book |last=Hennessy |first=Charles |title=Civil Procedure & Practice |publisher=W. Green |edition=4th |date=2014 |page=185}}</ref> A court will grant an interim interdict if there is a [[prima facie]] case and on the balance of convenience the remedy should be granted.<ref>{{cite book |last=MacQueen |first=Hector |title=Contract Law in Scotland |publisher=Tottel Publishing |edition=2nd |date=2007 |page=223}}</ref>  Breaching an interdict can result in a fine or imprisonment.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.macroberts.com/breach-of-interdict-a-cautionary-tale/ |title=Breach of interdict – a cautionary tale
|last=Breakey |first=Leon |date=9 January 2015 |access-date=17 May 2016 |website=MacRoberts LLP}}</ref>

