{{refimprove|date=November 2012}} [[File:US Map 2.png|alt=|thumb|400x400px|Map showing dry (red), wet (blue), and moist (yellow) counties in the United States]] In the [[United States]], a '''moist county''' is a [[County (United States)|county]] in between a "[[dry county]]" (where the [[sales|sale]] of [[alcoholic beverage]]s is [[prohibition of alcohol|prohibited]]) and a "[[wet county]]" (where alcohol is sold). The term is typically used for any county that allows alcohol to be sold in certain situations, but has limitations on alcohol sales that a normal "wet" county would not have. Some historically "dry" counties are switching to this system to avoid losing money to businesses in other counties, but do not wish to become completely "wet." The term in itself does not have any specific meaning, just that the county is not completely "wet" but is not "dry", either. The terms are applicable in states in which each county makes its own rules on alcohol sales. A "dry" county that contains one or more "wet" [[US cities|cities]] is typically called "moist".
== Examples ==
In [[Kentucky]], the term can be used in two different senses: *Two different [[Alcohol laws of Kentucky|statutes]] allow any dry territory—which can be a dry county or a city located in a dry county—to vote to authorize limited sales of alcoholic beverages by the drink in restaurants. Both statutes require that restaurants make at least 70% of their money from food (rather than alcohol) sales. One statute requires that the restaurant seat at least 100 patrons. The other, signed into law in June 2007, requires only 50 seats, but prohibits licensed establishments from having a dedicated bar and requires that the drinks be sold in association with a meal. Once a jurisdiction votes for such sales, qualifying restaurants can apply for a permit, which are distributed on a somewhat limited basis. For example, the [[Louisville, Kentucky|Louisville]] suburban jurisdiction of [[Oldham County, Kentucky|Oldham County]] voted to allow such sales in the early 2000s (its county seat of [[La Grange, Kentucky|La Grange]] later approved full package sales in 2012).<ref name="La Grange">{{cite news|url=http://www.wdrb.com/story/19111180/la-grange-votes-for-expanded-alcohol-sales |title=La Grange voters approve expanded alcohol sales |author=[[Associated Press]] |publisher=[[WDRB]] |date=July 25, 2012 |accessdate=July 26, 2012}}</ref> Note, however, that Kentucky's Office of Alcoholic Beverage Control does not use the term "moist county" to describe a county in which such sales are allowed, calling it instead a "limited" county.<ref name=KYABC>{{cite web |url=http://abc.ky.gov/Licensing/Wet%20Dry%20List%20-%20Revised%208-21-14.pdf |title=Wet-Dry-Moist Territories August 21, 2014 |publisher=Kentucky Office of Alcoholic Beverage Control |accessdate=September 2, 2014 |format=[[Portable Document Format|PDF]] |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141224030253/http://abc.ky.gov/Licensing/Wet%20Dry%20List%20-%20Revised%208-21-14.pdf |archivedate=December 24, 2014 |df= }}</ref> *Officially, a "moist county" is an otherwise dry county in which a city in the county's jurisdiction has voted to allow full retail sales of alcoholic beverages. The following Kentucky counties<ref name="La Grange"/><ref name=KYABC /> fall in this category: ::{| class="wikitable" !Dry county !Wet city or cities |- |[[Barren County, Kentucky|Barren]] |[[Cave City, Kentucky|Cave City]] |- |[[Boyd County, Kentucky|Boyd]]<ref>This county is also a "limited" county which has voted to allow qualifying restaurants outside the city of Ashland to sell alcoholic beverages by the drink. Minimum seating capacity is 100.</ref> |[[Ashland, Kentucky|Ashland]]<ref name="Getting wetter">{{cite news|url=http://dailyindependent.com/opinion/x333949536/Getting-wetter/print |title=Getting wetter |newspaper=[[The Independent (Ashland)|The Independent]] |location=Ashland, KY |date=June 21, 2012 |accessdate=August 24, 2012}}</ref><ref>According to the referenced story in Ashland's daily newspaper, the original 1981 vote that approved alcohol sales in Ashland only covered four precincts that include the city's downtown. Since then, two of the four precincts have voted themselves dry again.</ref> |- |rowspan=2 | [[Boyle County, Kentucky|Boyle]] |[[Danville, Kentucky|Danville]] |- |[[Junction City, Kentucky|Junction City]] |- | [[Caldwell County, Kentucky|Caldwell]] | [[Princeton, Kentucky|Princeton]]<ref name=WKMS>{{cite news|url=http://www.wkms.org/post/princeton-sturgis-vote-allow-alcohol-sales |title=Princeton & Sturgis Vote to Allow Alcohol Sales |first=Rose |last=Krzton-Presson |publisher=[[WKMS-FM]] |location=Murray, KY |date=August 7, 2012 |accessdate=August 24, 2012}}</ref> |- | [[Calloway County, Kentucky|Calloway]] | [[Murray, Kentucky|Murray]]<ref name="Murray vote">{{cite news|url=http://murrayledger.com/news/local/city-to-begin-its-alcohol-governance-discussion/article_ca3485c4-d58f-11e1-bdbb-0019bb2963f4.html |title=City to begin its alcohol governance discussion |first=Hawkins |last=Teague |newspaper=Murray Ledger & Times |date=July 24, 2012 |accessdate=July 26, 2012}}</ref> |- |rowspan=2 | [[Carter County, Kentucky|Carter]] |[[Grayson, Kentucky|Grayson]] |- |[[Olive Hill, Kentucky|Olive Hill]] |- |[[Clay County, Kentucky|Clay]] |[[Manchester, Kentucky|Manchester]] |- |[[Estill County, Kentucky|Estill]] |[[Irvine, Kentucky|Irvine]] |- |[[Fleming County, Kentucky|Fleming]] |[[Flemingsburg, Kentucky|Flemingsburg]] |- |[[Garrard County, Kentucky|Garrard]] |[[Lancaster, Kentucky|Lancaster]] |- |[[Greenup County, Kentucky|Greenup]] |[[Russell, Kentucky|Russell]] |- | rowspan=3 | [[Hardin County, Kentucky|Hardin]] |[[Elizabethtown, Kentucky|Elizabethtown]] |- |[[Radcliff, Kentucky|Radcliff]] |- |[[Vine Grove, Kentucky|Vine Grove]] |- |[[Harlan County, Kentucky|Harlan]] |[[Cumberland, Kentucky|Cumberland]] |- |[[Henry County, Kentucky|Henry]]<ref>This county is also a "limited" county which has voted to allow qualifying restaurants outside of the city of Eminence to sell alcoholic beverages by the drink. Minimum seating capacity is 50.</ref> |[[Eminence, Kentucky|Eminence]] |- |rowspan=4 | [[Hopkins County, Kentucky|Hopkins]] |[[Dawson Springs, Kentucky|Dawson Springs]] |- |[[Earlington, Kentucky|Earlington]] |- |[[Hanson, Kentucky|Hanson]] |- |[[Madisonville, Kentucky|Madisonville]] |- |[[Jessamine County, Kentucky|Jessamine]] |[[Nicholasville, Kentucky|Nicholasville]] |- |[[Johnson County, Kentucky|Johnson]] |[[Paintsville, Kentucky|Paintsville]] |- |[[Knox County, Kentucky|Knox]] |[[Corbin, Kentucky|Corbin]] |- |[[Laurel County, Kentucky|Laurel]] |[[London, Kentucky|London]] |- |[[Lewis County, Kentucky|Lewis]] |[[Vanceburg, Kentucky|Vanceburg]] |- |[[Logan County, Kentucky|Logan]] |[[Russellville, Kentucky|Russellville]] |- |[[Madison County, Kentucky|Madison]] |[[Richmond, Kentucky|Richmond]] |- |[[Montgomery County, Kentucky|Montgomery]] |[[Mount Sterling, Kentucky|Mount Sterling]] |- |[[Muhlenberg County, Kentucky|Muhlenberg]] |[[Cent