]] |[[Bowling Green, Kentucky|Bowling Green]] |- |[[Washington County, Kentucky|Washington]] |[[Springfield, Kentucky|Springfield]] |- |rowspan=2 |[[Whitley County, Kentucky|Whitley]] |[[Corbin, Kentucky|Corbin]] |- |[[Williamsburg, Kentucky|Williamsburg]] |}
Note that once a city votes itself fully wet, state law mandates a 60-day period, starting on the date that the election results are certified, before vendors can apply for licenses to sell distilled spirits and wine. At the end of that period, the state will then advertise in that city's newspaper of record to announce the number of licenses that will be granted. However, beer licenses are not subject to quotas, and can be applied for once the city enacts a governing ordinance.<ref name="Murray certified">{{cite news|url=http://murrayledger.com/news/local/wet-dry-results-certified-thursday/article_60a4e6e4-d274-11e1-b2af-0019bb2963f4.html |title=Wet-dry results certified Thursday |first=Hawkins |last=Teague |newspaper=Murray Ledger & Times |date=July 20, 2012 |accessdate=July 26, 2012}}</ref>
